//www.theguardian.com/music/2025/feb/22/british-library-acquires-torn-out-drafts-of-edward-elgar-masterpiece","summary":"<p>Exclusive: sketches for Introduction and Allegro for Strings had been removed from sketchbook by composer in 1930</p><p>The British Library has acquired previously unknown sketches and drafts by Sir Edward Elgar for one of his best-known masterpieces, Introduction and Allegro for Strings.</p><p>Spanning 15 pages, they shed light on the creative process of Britain’s most revered composer. One bears the beginnings of an unknown organ piece on which he had started work.</p> <a href=\\"https://www.theguardian.com/music/2025/feb/22/british-library-acquires-torn-out-drafts-of-edward-elgar-masterpiece\\">Continue reading...</a>","summary_detail":{"type":"text/html","language":null,"base":"","value":"<p>Exclusive: sketches for Introduction and Allegro for Strings had been removed from sketchbook by composer in 1930</p><p>The British Library has acquired previously unknown sketches and drafts by Sir Edward Elgar for one of his best-known masterpieces, Introduction and Allegro for Strings.</p><p>Spanning 15 pages, they shed light on the creative process of Britain’s most revered composer. One bears the beginnings of an unknown organ piece on which he had started work.</p> <a href=\\"https://www.theguardian.com/music/2025/feb/22/british-library-acquires-torn-out-drafts-of-edward-elgar-masterpiece\\">Continue reading...</a>"},"tags":[{"term":"Edward Elgar","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/music/edward-elgar","label":null},{"term":"Classical music","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/music/classical-music-and-opera","label":null},{"term":"British Library","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/books/british-library","label":null},{"term":"Music","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/music/music","label":null},{"term":"Culture","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/culture/culture","label":null},{"term":"UK news","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/uk/uk","label":null}],"published":"Sat, 22 Feb 2025 08:00:01 GMT","published_parsed":[2025,2,22,8,0,1,5,53,0],"id":"https://www.theguardian.com/music/2025/feb/22/british-library-acquires-torn-out-drafts-of-edward-elgar-masterpiece","guidislink":false,"media_content":[{"width":"140","url":"https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/c28e7bef46565171e1eaea075dea27f3a8704e21/116_0_3780_2268/master/3780.jpg?width=140&quality=85&auto=format&fit=max&s=619063194469499e14963bc2f6f0a27e"},{"width":"460","url":"https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/c28e7bef46565171e1eaea075dea27f3a8704e21/116_0_3780_2268/master/3780.jpg?width=460&quality=85&auto=format&fit=max&s=8bdb2f05f79fb38915bd65bd4b85d964"}],"media_credit":[{"scheme":"urn:ebu","content":"Photograph: The British Library Board"},{"scheme":"urn:ebu","content":"Photograph: The British Library Board"}],"credit":"Photograph: The British Library Board","authors":[{"name":"Dalya Alberge"}],"author":"Dalya Alberge","author_detail":{"name":"Dalya Alberge"},"updated":"2025-02-22T08:00:01Z","updated_parsed":[2025,2,22,8,0,1,5,53,0]},{"title":"Young country diary: A winter festival of ivy","title_detail":{"type":"text/plain","language":null,"base":"","value":"Young country diary: A winter festival of ivy"},"links":[{"rel":"alternate","type":"text/html","href":"https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2025/feb/22/young-country-diary-a-winter-festival-of-ivy"}],"link":"https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2025/feb/22/young-country-diary-a-winter-festival-of-ivy","summary":"<p><strong>Chepstow, Monmouthshire:</strong> It seems to cover everything, on the ground and on the trees. Thankfully, lots of wildlife is grateful for it</p><p>Have you ever noticed that ivy eventually takes over everything? All up the trees. All over the floor. In the winter, it makes the grey trees look full of life again. It comes in different shapes, different colours, but it all does the same thing: takes over the woodland. The vines snake along the ground, taking everything in their path.</p><p>This all came to my attention during a frosty walk through my local woods with my family. All the puddles had frozen over and my little brother and I had fun smashing the ice to see who could pick up the biggest bit (I did because mine was massive!)</p> <a href=\\"https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2025/feb/22/young-country-diary-a-winter-festival-of-ivy\\">Continue reading...</a>","summary_detail":{"type":"text/html","language":null,"base":"","value":"<p><strong>Chepstow, Monmouthshire:</strong> It seems to cover everything, on the ground and on the trees. Thankfully, lots of wildlife is grateful for it</p><p>Have you ever noticed that ivy eventually takes over everything? All up the trees. All over the floor. In the winter, it makes the grey trees look full of life again. It comes in different shapes, different colours, but it all does the same thing: takes over the woodland. The vines snake along the ground, taking everything in their path.</p><p>This all came to my attention during a frosty walk through my local woods with my family. All the puddles had frozen over and my little brother and I had fun smashing the ice to see who could pick up the biggest bit (I did because mine was massive!)</p> <a href=\\"https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2025/feb/22/young-country-diary-a-winter-festival-of-ivy\\">Continue reading...</a>"},"tags":[{"term":"Plants","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/environment/plants","label":null},{"term":"Environment","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/environment/environment","label":null},{"term":"Rural affairs","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/uk/ruralaffairs","label":null},{"term":"UK news","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/uk/uk","label":null}],"published":"Sat, 22 Feb 2025 11:01:04 GMT","published_parsed":[2025,2,22,11,1,4,5,53,0],"id":"https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2025/feb/22/young-country-diary-a-winter-festival-of-ivy","guidislink":false,"media_content":[{"width":"140","url":"https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/a363e6c7b2f6d1112aca1467c5de57adc32eb1d0/0_87_4000_2400/master/4000.jpg?width=140&quality=85&auto=format&fit=max&s=c774af9ef5d9cdc390f0b83b3e742e66"},{"width":"460","url":"https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/a363e6c7b2f6d1112aca1467c5de57adc32eb1d0/0_87_4000_2400/master/4000.jpg?width=460&quality=85&auto=format&fit=max&s=1aa5992f8b466c16e24ccbd674eaf7cb"}],"media_credit":[{"scheme":"urn:ebu","content":"Photograph: John Gilbey"},{"scheme":"urn:ebu","content":"Photograph: John Gilbey"}],"credit":"Photograph: John Gilbey","authors":[{}],"author":"","updated":"2025-02-22T11:01:04Z","updated_parsed":[2025,2,22,11,1,4,5,53,0]},{"title":"Republicans put the sick in sycophancy as they compete to fawn over Trump","title_detail":{"type":"text/plain","language":null,"base":"","value":"Republicans put the sick in sycophancy as they compete to fawn over Trump"},"links":[{"rel":"alternate","type":"text/html","href":"https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2025/feb/22/trump-republicans-mount-rushmore-third-term"}],"link":"https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2025/feb/22/trump-republicans-mount-rushmore-third-term","summary":"<p>From adding the president’s face to Mount Rushmore to pushing for him to serve a third term, party members are getting inventive in their brown-nosing</p><p>If proof were needed that Donald Trump’s <a href=\\"https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/article/2024/aug/03/trump-maga-suporters-explain-republican\\">cult of personality</a> has never been stronger, it comes in the inventive ways Republican members of Congress have spent his first month in office trying to lionise him. Welcome to the sycophancy stakes.</p><p>On 23 January the congressman Addison McDowell of North Carolina <a href=\\"https://mcdowell.house.gov/media/press-releases/congressman-addison-mcdowell-introduces-legislation-rename-washington-dulles#:~:text=WASHINGTON%2C%20D.C.%20%E2%80%93%20Today%2C%20Congressman,Trump%20International%20Airport.\\">introduced legislation</a> to rename Washington Dulles international airport as Donald J Trump international airport.</p> <a href=\\"https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2025/feb/22/trump-republicans-mount-rushmore-third-term\\">Continue reading...</a>","summary_detail":{"type":"text/html","language":null,"base":"","value":"<p>From adding the president’s face to Mount Rushmore to pushing for him to serve a third term, party members are getting inventive in their brown-nosing</p><p>If proof were needed that Donald Trump’s <a href=\\"https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/article/2024/aug/03/trump-maga-suporters-explain-republican\\">cult of personality</a> has never been stronger, it comes in the inventive ways Republican members of Congress have spent his first month in office trying to lionise him. Welcome to the sycophancy stakes.</p><p>On 23 January the congressman Addison McDowell of North Carolina <a href=\\"https://mcdowell.house.gov/media/press-releases/congressman-addison-mcdowell-introduces-legislation-rename-washington-dulles#:~:text=WASHINGTON%2C%20D.C.%20%E2%80%93%20Today%2C%20Congressman,Trump%20International%20Airport.\\">introduced legislation</a> to rename Washington Dulles international airport as Donald J Trump international airport.</p> <a href=\\"https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2025/feb/22/trump-republicans-mount-rushmore-third-term\\">Continue reading...</a>"},"tags":[{"term":"Donald Trump","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/donaldtrump","label":null},{"term":"Republicans","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/republicans","label":null},{"term":"US news","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/us-news","label":null},{"term":"US Congress","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/us-congress","label":null},{"term":"House of Representatives","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/house-of-representatives","label":null},{"term":"US politics","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/us-politics","label":null}],"published":"Sat, 22 Feb 2025 11:00:04 GMT","published_parsed":[2025,2,22,11,0,4,5,53,0],"id":"https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2025/feb/22/trump-republicans-mount-rushmore-third-term","guidislink":false,"media_content":[{"width":"140","url":"https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/3ef29081574ddce96f3a6ff447c371ab46b7691c/0_0_1500_900/master/1500.jpg?width=140&quality=85&auto=format&fit=max&s=8f25379d50368054ac6a8eeb24903bdd"},{"width":"460","url":"https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/3ef29081574ddce96f3a6ff447c371ab46b7691c/0_0_1500_900/master/1500.jpg?width=460&quality=85&auto=format&fit=max&s=37d180842ce290a0e7dbd34c7ee6cece"}],"media_credit":[{"scheme":"urn:ebu","content":"Composite: The Guardian/Getty Images"},{"scheme":"urn:ebu","content":"Composite: The Guardian/Getty Images"}],"credit":"Composite: The Guardian/Getty Images","authors":[{"name":"David Smith in Washington"}],"author":"David Smith in Washington","author_detail":{"name":"David Smith in Washington"},"updated":"2025-02-22T11:00:04Z","updated_parsed":[2025,2,22,11,0,4,5,53,0]},{"title":"A train through Germany: is Europe’s powerhouse going off the rails?","title_detail":{"type":"text/plain","language":null,"base":"","value":"A train through Germany: is Europe’s powerhouse going off the rails?"},"links":[{"rel":"alternate","type":"text/html","href":"https://www.theguardian.com/world/2025/feb/22/a-train-through-germany-is-europes-powerhouse-going-off-the-rails"}],"link":"https://www.theguardian.com/world/2025/feb/22/a-train-through-germany-is-europes-powerhouse-going-off-the-rails","summary":"<p>In the run-up to Sunday’s crucial election, the Guardian took a long journey through Europe’s heartland to talk to voters</p><p>Creaking, overcrowded, neglected, Germany’s railways, once a source of national pride, have taken a battering to their image in recent years. Amid wider concerns about the health of Europe’s stagnating largest economy, the state of its trains has become something of a metaphor for a more general sense of malaise.</p><p>On Sunday Germans will go to the polls in one of the most important elections in recent times, with an emboldened far right hoping to more than double its share of votes. In the run-up, the Guardian travelled more than 850 miles on trains across Germany to hear what its citizens have to say about the state of their nation.</p> <a href=\\"https://www.theguardian.com/world/2025/feb/22/a-train-through-germany-is-europes-powerhouse-going-off-the-rails\\">Continue reading...</a>","summary_detail":{"type":"text/html","language":null,"base":"","value":"<p>In the run-up to Sunday’s crucial election, the Guardian took a long journey through Europe’s heartland to talk to voters</p><p>Creaking, overcrowded, neglected, Germany’s railways, once a source of national pride, have taken a battering to their image in recent years. Amid wider concerns about the health of Europe’s stagnating largest economy, the state of its trains has become something of a metaphor for a more general sense of malaise.</p><p>On Sunday Germans will go to the polls in one of the most important elections in recent times, with an emboldened far right hoping to more than double its share of votes. In the run-up, the Guardian travelled more than 850 miles on trains across Germany to hear what its citizens have to say about the state of their nation.</p> <a href=\\"https://www.theguardian.com/world/2025/feb/22/a-train-through-germany-is-europes-powerhouse-going-off-the-rails\\">Continue reading...</a>"},"tags":[{"term":"Germany","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/world/germany","label":null},{"term":"Europe","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/world/europe-news","label":null},{"term":"The far right","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/world/far-right","label":null},{"term":"Alternative für Deutschland (AfD)","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/world/alternative-fur-deutschland-afd","label":null},{"term":"Migration","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/world/migration","label":null}],"published":"Sat, 22 Feb 2025 05:00:07 GMT","published_parsed":[2025,2,22,5,0,7,5,53,0],"id":"https://www.theguardian.com/world/2025/feb/22/a-train-through-germany-is-europes-powerhouse-going-off-the-rails","guidislink":false,"media_content":[{"width":"140","url":"https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/84bf86e069bf61cc8dc88ebf97e7a7350c9ff7f6/0_71_9528_5721/master/9528.jpg?width=140&quality=85&auto=format&fit=max&s=e0f029e0c867c5116f4e110a65129d5c"},{"width":"460","url":"https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/84bf86e069bf61cc8dc88ebf97e7a7350c9ff7f6/0_71_9528_5721/master/9528.jpg?width=460&quality=85&auto=format&fit=max&s=a00a9a103b6c8ec17abe1aff20d1a49a"}],"media_credit":[{"scheme":"urn:ebu","content":"Photograph: Sean Smith/The Guardian"},{"scheme":"urn:ebu","content":"Photograph: Sean Smith/The Guardian"}],"credit":"Photograph: Sean Smith/The Guardian","authors":[{"name":"Kate Connolly, photographs by Sean Smith"}],"author":"Kate Connolly, photographs by Sean Smith","author_detail":{"name":"Kate Connolly, photographs by Sean Smith"},"updated":"2025-02-22T05:00:07Z","updated_parsed":[2025,2,22,5,0,7,5,53,0]},{"title":"Space mission aims to map water on surface of the moon","title_detail":{"type":"text/plain","language":null,"base":"","value":"Space mission aims to map water on surface of the moon"},"links":[{"rel":"alternate","type":"text/html","href":"https://www.theguardian.com/science/2025/feb/22/space-mission-aims-to-map-water-on-surface-of-the-moon"}],"link":"https://www.theguardian.com/science/2025/feb/22/space-mission-aims-to-map-water-on-surface-of-the-moon","summary":"<p>A probe to be launched this week aims to pinpoint sites of lunar water, which could help plan to colonise the Earth’s satellite</p><p>Space engineers are set to launch an unusual mission this week when they send a probe built by UK and US researchers to the moon to map water on its surface. Lunar Trailblazer’s two year mission is scheduled to begin on Thursday when the probe is blasted into space from Florida on a Space X Falcon&nbsp;rocket.</p><p>Its goal – to seek out water on the lunar surface – may seem odd given that the moon has traditionally been viewed as an arid, desiccated world. However, scientists have recently uncovered strong hints that it possesses significant quantities of water. It will be the task of Lunar Trailblazer to reveal just how much water there is near the lunar surface and pinpoint its main locations.</p> <a href=\\"https://www.theguardian.com/science/2025/feb/22/space-mission-aims-to-map-water-on-surface-of-the-moon\\">Continue reading...</a>","summary_detail":{"type":"text/html","language":null,"base":"","value":"<p>A probe to be launched this week aims to pinpoint sites of lunar water, which could help plan to colonise the Earth’s satellite</p><p>Space engineers are set to launch an unusual mission this week when they send a probe built by UK and US researchers to the moon to map water on its surface. Lunar Trailblazer’s two year mission is scheduled to begin on Thursday when the probe is blasted into space from Florida on a Space X Falcon&nbsp;rocket.</p><p>Its goal – to seek out water on the lunar surface – may seem odd given that the moon has traditionally been viewed as an arid, desiccated world. However, scientists have recently uncovered strong hints that it possesses significant quantities of water. It will be the task of Lunar Trailblazer to reveal just how much water there is near the lunar surface and pinpoint its main locations.</p> <a href=\\"https://www.theguardian.com/science/2025/feb/22/space-mission-aims-to-map-water-on-surface-of-the-moon\\">Continue reading...</a>"},"tags":[{"term":"The moon","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/science/moon","label":null},{"term":"Space","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/science/space","label":null},{"term":"Nasa","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/science/nasa","label":null},{"term":"Science","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/science/science","label":null},{"term":"World news","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/world/world","label":null}],"published":"Sat, 22 Feb 2025 16:56:34 GMT","published_parsed":[2025,2,22,16,56,34,5,53,0],"id":"https://www.theguardian.com/science/2025/feb/22/space-mission-aims-to-map-water-on-surface-of-the-moon","guidislink":false,"media_content":[{"width":"140","url":"https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/fde66959b8efefcbcd5bdc8dffac78a904d7d630/435_592_4786_2871/master/4786.jpg?width=140&quality=85&auto=format&fit=max&s=22cb466216bd560242edd796f856bd52"},{"width":"460","url":"https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/fde66959b8efefcbcd5bdc8dffac78a904d7d630/435_592_4786_2871/master/4786.jpg?width=460&quality=85&auto=format&fit=max&s=e613ac98039b10f8f356914dbbe6566f"}],"media_credit":[{"scheme":"urn:ebu","content":"Photograph: Jordan Salkin/GRC/NASA"},{"scheme":"urn:ebu","content":"Photograph: Jordan Salkin/GRC/NASA"}],"credit":"Photograph: Jordan Salkin/GRC/NASA","authors":[{"name":"Robin McKie, science editor"}],"author":"Robin McKie, science editor","author_detail":{"name":"Robin McKie, science editor"},"updated":"2025-02-22T16:56:34Z","updated_parsed":[2025,2,22,16,56,34,5,53,0]},{"title":"Grosse Pointe Blank and Miami Blues director George Armitage dies aged 82","title_detail":{"type":"text/plain","language":null,"base":"","value":"Grosse Pointe Blank and Miami Blues director George Armitage dies aged 82"},"links":[{"rel":"alternate","type":"text/html","href":"https://www.theguardian.com/film/2025/feb/22/grosse-pointe-blank-and-miami-blues-director-george-armitage-dies-aged-82"}],"link":"https://www.theguardian.com/film/2025/feb/22/grosse-pointe-blank-and-miami-blues-director-george-armitage-dies-aged-82","summary":"<p>Armitage was also responsible for the 1972 blaxploitation remake of Get Carter, made during his time working for Roger Corman</p><p>George Armitage, director of 90s indie hits Grosse Pointe Blank and Miami Blues, as well as Hit Man, the 70s blaxploitation remake of Get Carter, has died aged 82. <a href=\\"https://variety.com/2025/film/news/george-armitage-dead-grosse-pointe-blank-miami-blues-1236316150\\">Variety reported</a> he died on 15 February in Playa del Rey in California.</p><p>Armitage started out in TV, working on the celebrated TV soap opera Peyton Place, then broke into features via Roger Corman’s micro-budget studio New World in the late 1960s. He subsequently specialised in crime films: Grosse Pointe Blank, which starred John Cusack and Minnie Driver, was his biggest commercial hit, and his final directorial credit was the Elmore Leonard adaptation The Big Bounce in 2004.</p> <a href=\\"https://www.theguardian.com/film/2025/feb/22/grosse-pointe-blank-and-miami-blues-director-george-armitage-dies-aged-82\\">Continue reading...</a>","summary_detail":{"type":"text/html","language":null,"base":"","value":"<p>Armitage was also responsible for the 1972 blaxploitation remake of Get Carter, made during his time working for Roger Corman</p><p>George Armitage, director of 90s indie hits Grosse Pointe Blank and Miami Blues, as well as Hit Man, the 70s blaxploitation remake of Get Carter, has died aged 82. <a href=\\"https://variety.com/2025/film/news/george-armitage-dead-grosse-pointe-blank-miami-blues-1236316150\\">Variety reported</a> he died on 15 February in Playa del Rey in California.</p><p>Armitage started out in TV, working on the celebrated TV soap opera Peyton Place, then broke into features via Roger Corman’s micro-budget studio New World in the late 1960s. He subsequently specialised in crime films: Grosse Pointe Blank, which starred John Cusack and Minnie Driver, was his biggest commercial hit, and his final directorial credit was the Elmore Leonard adaptation The Big Bounce in 2004.</p> <a href=\\"https://www.theguardian.com/film/2025/feb/22/grosse-pointe-blank-and-miami-blues-director-george-armitage-dies-aged-82\\">Continue reading...</a>"},"tags":[{"term":"Film","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/film/film","label":null},{"term":"John Cusack","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/film/john-cusack","label":null},{"term":"Film adaptations","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/film/film-adaptations","label":null},{"term":"Elmore Leonard","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/books/elmoreleonard","label":null},{"term":"Books","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/books/books","label":null},{"term":"Culture","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/culture/culture","label":null}],"published":"Sat, 22 Feb 2025 14:00:28 GMT","published_parsed":[2025,2,22,14,0,28,5,53,0],"id":"https://www.theguardian.com/film/2025/feb/22/grosse-pointe-blank-and-miami-blues-director-george-armitage-dies-aged-82","guidislink":false,"media_content":[{"width":"140","url":"https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/05197a01dc5636fba6a6e9ef328b833e9231c572/0_174_4000_2400/master/4000.jpg?width=140&quality=85&auto=format&fit=max&s=26ca6dd97d931d085fd94168b5d8fbc7"},{"width":"460","url":"https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/05197a01dc5636fba6a6e9ef328b833e9231c572/0_174_4000_2400/master/4000.jpg?width=460&quality=85&auto=format&fit=max&s=e1f7fb6ece984f401a9d79ddcc0d953c"}],"media_credit":[{"scheme":"urn:ebu","content":"Photograph: United Archives GmbH/Alamy"},{"scheme":"urn:ebu","content":"Photograph: United Archives GmbH/Alamy"}],"credit":"Photograph: United Archives GmbH/Alamy","authors":[{"name":"Andrew Pulver"}],"author":"Andrew Pulver","author_detail":{"name":"Andrew Pulver"},"updated":"2025-02-22T14:00:28Z","updated_parsed":[2025,2,22,14,0,28,5,53,0]},{"title":"Are noise-cancelling headphones impairing our hearing skills? Some audiologists are beginning to worry","title_detail":{"type":"text/plain","language":null,"base":"","value":"Are noise-cancelling headphones impairing our hearing skills? Some audiologists are beginning to worry"},"links":[{"rel":"alternate","type":"text/html","href":"https://www.theguardian.com/science/2025/feb/22/filter-trouble-why-audiologists-worry-noise-cancelling-headphones-may-impair-hearing-skills"}],"link":"https://www.theguardian.com/science/2025/feb/22/filter-trouble-why-audiologists-worry-noise-cancelling-headphones-may-impair-hearing-skills","summary":"<p>Some specialists suspect that constantly filtering out background noise may have unintended consequences</p><p>They are prized for making the commute more bearable and shielding against the din of daily life. But noise-cancelling headphones have come under scrutiny after audiologists raised concerns that overuse might impair people’s hearing skills.</p><p>While the technology has clear benefits, not least in helping people listen to music at lower volume, some specialists suspect that constantly filtering out background noise may have unintended consequences.</p> <a href=\\"https://www.theguardian.com/science/2025/feb/22/filter-trouble-why-audiologists-worry-noise-cancelling-headphones-may-impair-hearing-skills\\">Continue reading...</a>","summary_detail":{"type":"text/html","language":null,"base":"","value":"<p>Some specialists suspect that constantly filtering out background noise may have unintended consequences</p><p>They are prized for making the commute more bearable and shielding against the din of daily life. But noise-cancelling headphones have come under scrutiny after audiologists raised concerns that overuse might impair people’s hearing skills.</p><p>While the technology has clear benefits, not least in helping people listen to music at lower volume, some specialists suspect that constantly filtering out background noise may have unintended consequences.</p> <a href=\\"https://www.theguardian.com/science/2025/feb/22/filter-trouble-why-audiologists-worry-noise-cancelling-headphones-may-impair-hearing-skills\\">Continue reading...</a>"},"tags":[{"term":"Science","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/science/science","label":null},{"term":"Health","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/society/health","label":null},{"term":"Technology","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/technology/technology","label":null}],"published":"Sat, 22 Feb 2025 05:00:06 GMT","published_parsed":[2025,2,22,5,0,6,5,53,0],"id":"https://www.theguardian.com/science/2025/feb/22/filter-trouble-why-audiologists-worry-noise-cancelling-headphones-may-impair-hearing-skills","guidislink":false,"media_content":[{"width":"140","url":"https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/3fd46e7a527a8f9279f12f9df78f5e94151ed235/1337_732_6773_4066/master/6773.jpg?width=140&quality=85&auto=format&fit=max&s=2a1346bcc33388366f6a8603b4d8fad8"},{"width":"460","url":"https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/3fd46e7a527a8f9279f12f9df78f5e94151ed235/1337_732_6773_4066/master/6773.jpg?width=460&quality=85&auto=format&fit=max&s=0f17a10d2aab2ef3428fd9fb8be4b94e"}],"media_credit":[{"scheme":"urn:ebu","content":"Photograph: kali9/Getty Images"},{"scheme":"urn:ebu","content":"Photograph: kali9/Getty Images"}],"credit":"Photograph: kali9/Getty Images","authors":[{"name":"Ian Sample Science editor"}],"author":"Ian Sample Science editor","author_detail":{"name":"Ian Sample Science editor"},"updated":"2025-02-22T05:00:06Z","updated_parsed":[2025,2,22,5,0,6,5,53,0]},{"title":"Konstantin Kisin: anti-woke libertarian who reluctantly calls himself ‘right wing’","title_detail":{"type":"text/plain","language":null,"base":"","value":"Konstantin Kisin: anti-woke libertarian who reluctantly calls himself ‘right wing’"},"links":[{"rel":"alternate","type":"text/html","href":"https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2025/feb/22/konstantin-kisin-anti-woke-libertarian-reluctantly-calls-himself-right-wing"}],"link":"https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2025/feb/22/konstantin-kisin-anti-woke-libertarian-reluctantly-calls-himself-right-wing","summary":"<p>In speech at Arc conference, podcaster argues ‘identity politics and multiculturalism … are two failed experiments’</p><p>Konstantin Kisin has until this week been best known as a libertarian, pro-free speech independent podcaster, and for a viral appearance at the Oxford Union arguing that “woke culture has gone too far”.</p><p>His profile has suddenly risen, however, after hosting the Conservative leader, Kemi Badenoch, on his podcast, and arguing in an episode with Fraser Nelson, the former editor of the Spectator, that Rishi Sunak was not English owing to his “brown Hindu” background – triggering criticism on social media.</p> <a href=\\"https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2025/feb/22/konstantin-kisin-anti-woke-libertarian-reluctantly-calls-himself-right-wing\\">Continue reading...</a>","summary_detail":{"type":"text/html","language":null,"base":"","value":"<p>In speech at Arc conference, podcaster argues ‘identity politics and multiculturalism … are two failed experiments’</p><p>Konstantin Kisin has until this week been best known as a libertarian, pro-free speech independent podcaster, and for a viral appearance at the Oxford Union arguing that “woke culture has gone too far”.</p><p>His profile has suddenly risen, however, after hosting the Conservative leader, Kemi Badenoch, on his podcast, and arguing in an episode with Fraser Nelson, the former editor of the Spectator, that Rishi Sunak was not English owing to his “brown Hindu” background – triggering criticism on social media.</p> <a href=\\"https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2025/feb/22/konstantin-kisin-anti-woke-libertarian-reluctantly-calls-himself-right-wing\\">Continue reading...</a>"},"tags":[{"term":"Politics","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/politics/politics","label":null},{"term":"Freedom of speech","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/world/freedom-of-speech","label":null},{"term":"Social media","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/media/social-media","label":null},{"term":"Russia","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/world/russia","label":null},{"term":"Media","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/media/media","label":null},{"term":"UK news","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/uk/uk","label":null},{"term":"Donald Trump","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/donaldtrump","label":null}],"published":"Sat, 22 Feb 2025 06:00:05 GMT","published_parsed":[2025,2,22,6,0,5,5,53,0],"id":"https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2025/feb/22/konstantin-kisin-anti-woke-libertarian-reluctantly-calls-himself-right-wing","guidislink":false,"media_content":[{"width":"140","url":"https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/414146c441c2a310adf3437a5db27f7ef0e192a2/0_269_3084_1851/master/3084.jpg?width=140&quality=85&auto=format&fit=max&s=40823272108dc01d8ab07bd969d7dd2e"},{"width":"460","url":"https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/414146c441c2a310adf3437a5db27f7ef0e192a2/0_269_3084_1851/master/3084.jpg?width=460&quality=85&auto=format&fit=max&s=1713f05eb20d72cf44df040d737c3e0d"}],"media_credit":[{"scheme":"urn:ebu","content":"Photograph: S Meddle/ITV/Shutterstock"},{"scheme":"urn:ebu","content":"Photograph: S Meddle/ITV/Shutterstock"}],"credit":"Photograph: S Meddle/ITV/Shutterstock","authors":[{"name":"Rowena Mason Whitehall editor"}],"author":"Rowena Mason Whitehall editor","author_detail":{"name":"Rowena Mason Whitehall editor"},"updated":"2025-02-22T06:00:05Z","updated_parsed":[2025,2,22,6,0,5,5,53,0]},{"title":"Woman charged in dating app druggings and one death of older men in Las Vegas","title_detail":{"type":"text/plain","language":null,"base":"","value":"Woman charged in dating app druggings and one death of older men in Las Vegas"},"links":[{"rel":"alternate","type":"text/html","href":"https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2025/feb/22/las-vegas-dating-app-druggings-death"}],"link":"https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2025/feb/22/las-vegas-dating-app-druggings-death","summary":"<p>FBI says Aurora Phelps met men online for dating then drugged them and stole cars and money</p><p>A woman used online dating apps to lure at least four older men to meet her in person, drugged them with sedatives and stole hundreds of thousands of dollars in a “sinister” romance scheme, <a href=\\"https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/fbi\\">FBI</a> officials in Las Vegas said on Friday.</p><p>Three of the men died, authorities said, and she has been charged in one of their deaths.</p> <a href=\\"https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2025/feb/22/las-vegas-dating-app-druggings-death\\">Continue reading...</a>","summary_detail":{"type":"text/html","language":null,"base":"","value":"<p>FBI says Aurora Phelps met men online for dating then drugged them and stole cars and money</p><p>A woman used online dating apps to lure at least four older men to meet her in person, drugged them with sedatives and stole hundreds of thousands of dollars in a “sinister” romance scheme, <a href=\\"https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/fbi\\">FBI</a> officials in Las Vegas said on Friday.</p><p>Three of the men died, authorities said, and she has been charged in one of their deaths.</p> <a href=\\"https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2025/feb/22/las-vegas-dating-app-druggings-death\\">Continue reading...</a>"},"tags":[{"term":"Las Vegas","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/las-vegas","label":null},{"term":"US crime","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/us-crime","label":null},{"term":"FBI","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/fbi","label":null},{"term":"Mexico","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/world/mexico","label":null},{"term":"US news","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/us-news","label":null},{"term":"Americas","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/world/americas","label":null},{"term":"World news","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/world/world","label":null}],"published":"Sat, 22 Feb 2025 14:51:47 GMT","published_parsed":[2025,2,22,14,51,47,5,53,0],"id":"https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2025/feb/22/las-vegas-dating-app-druggings-death","guidislink":false,"media_content":[{"width":"140","url":"https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/5f1de8184d5bb27bf85bc876193f796c5227510a/204_1010_3046_1828/master/3046.jpg?width=140&quality=85&auto=format&fit=max&s=102cfa3a6cb4b89da68dd52637df8dd2"},{"width":"460","url":"https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/5f1de8184d5bb27bf85bc876193f796c5227510a/204_1010_3046_1828/master/3046.jpg?width=460&quality=85&auto=format&fit=max&s=8617c07492d953c6ec25c6ed9aec0f18"}],"media_credit":[{"scheme":"urn:ebu","content":"Photograph: Ty ONeil/AP"},{"scheme":"urn:ebu","content":"Photograph: Ty ONeil/AP"}],"credit":"Photograph: Ty ONeil/AP","authors":[{"name":"Associated Press"}],"author":"Associated Press","author_detail":{"name":"Associated Press"},"updated":"2025-02-22T14:51:47Z","updated_parsed":[2025,2,22,14,51,47,5,53,0]},{"title":"Alarm as bird flu now ‘endemic in cows’ while Trump cuts staff and funding","title_detail":{"type":"text/plain","language":null,"base":"","value":"Alarm as bird flu now ‘endemic in cows’ while Trump cuts staff and funding"},"links":[{"rel":"alternate","type":"text/html","href":"https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2025/feb/22/bird-flu-virus-trump"}],"link":"https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2025/feb/22/bird-flu-virus-trump","summary":"<p>Experts say current US outbreak is unlikely to end without intervention with further mutation of virus likely</p><p>A newer variant of <a href=\\"https://www.theguardian.com/world/bird-flu\\">H5N1 bird flu</a> has spilled over into dairy cows separately in Nevada and Arizona, prompting new theories about how the virus is spread and leading to questions about containing the ongoing outbreaks.</p><p>The news comes amid a purge of experts at federal agencies, including employees who were responding to the highly pathogenic avian influenza outbreak at the US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) and the US Department of Agriculture.</p> <a href=\\"https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2025/feb/22/bird-flu-virus-trump\\">Continue reading...</a>","summary_detail":{"type":"text/html","language":null,"base":"","value":"<p>Experts say current US outbreak is unlikely to end without intervention with further mutation of virus likely</p><p>A newer variant of <a href=\\"https://www.theguardian.com/world/bird-flu\\">H5N1 bird flu</a> has spilled over into dairy cows separately in Nevada and Arizona, prompting new theories about how the virus is spread and leading to questions about containing the ongoing outbreaks.</p><p>The news comes amid a purge of experts at federal agencies, including employees who were responding to the highly pathogenic avian influenza outbreak at the US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) and the US Department of Agriculture.</p> <a href=\\"https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2025/feb/22/bird-flu-virus-trump\\">Continue reading...</a>"},"tags":[{"term":"US news","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/us-news","label":null},{"term":"Trump administration","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/trump-administration","label":null},{"term":"Bird flu","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/world/bird-flu","label":null},{"term":"Science","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/science/science","label":null}],"published":"Sat, 22 Feb 2025 13:00:07 GMT","published_parsed":[2025,2,22,13,0,7,5,53,0],"id":"https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2025/feb/22/bird-flu-virus-trump","guidislink":false,"media_content":[{"width":"140","url":"https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/73c6759f879ebbf9781e71d99596ac7a866fed3b/0_0_5376_3226/master/5376.jpg?width=140&quality=85&auto=format&fit=max&s=d71272b6d883adeb1efcd58d97e4058a"},{"width":"460","url":"https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/73c6759f879ebbf9781e71d99596ac7a866fed3b/0_0_5376_3226/master/5376.jpg?width=460&quality=85&auto=format&fit=max&s=5ca2bee05b4ee0a283e373044137e331"}],"media_credit":[{"scheme":"urn:ebu","content":"Photograph: Jim West/Alamy"},{"scheme":"urn:ebu","content":"Photograph: Jim West/Alamy"}],"credit":"Photograph: Jim West/Alamy","authors":[{"name":"Melody Schreiber"}],"author":"Melody Schreiber","author_detail":{"name":"Melody Schreiber"},"updated":"2025-02-22T13:00:07Z","updated_parsed":[2025,2,22,13,0,7,5,53,0]},{"title":"‘Like a giant Squid Game’: soul searching in South Korea after latest celebrity suicide","title_detail":{"type":"text/plain","language":null,"base":"","value":"‘Like a giant Squid Game’: soul searching in South Korea after latest celebrity suicide"},"links":[{"rel":"alternate","type":"text/html","href":"https://www.theguardian.com/world/2025/feb/22/like-a-giant-squid-game-soul-searching-in-south-korea-after-latest-celebrity-suicide"}],"link":"https://www.theguardian.com/world/2025/feb/22/like-a-giant-squid-game-soul-searching-in-south-korea-after-latest-celebrity-suicide","summary":"<p>Death of actor Kim Sae-ron sparks renewed calls for changes to ease pressure on celebrities who face intense scrutiny from media and fans alike </p><p>On Friday, the South Korean columnist Yang Sung-hee <a href=\\"https://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/2025-02-21/opinion/columns/Koreas-relentless-cycle-of-celebrity-tragedy/2246373\\">asked</a> a question to which no one appears to have an answer: “When will this ever end? How many more lives must be lost before this tragic cycle is broken?”</p><p>Yang’s question, asked in the Korea JoongAng Daily newspaper, is just one of many that has emerged since the actor Kim Sae-ron was found dead in her home in Seoul on Sunday in a case police are treating as suicide. She was 24.</p> <a href=\\"https://www.theguardian.com/world/2025/feb/22/like-a-giant-squid-game-soul-searching-in-south-korea-after-latest-celebrity-suicide\\">Continue reading...</a>","summary_detail":{"type":"text/html","language":null,"base":"","value":"<p>Death of actor Kim Sae-ron sparks renewed calls for changes to ease pressure on celebrities who face intense scrutiny from media and fans alike </p><p>On Friday, the South Korean columnist Yang Sung-hee <a href=\\"https://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/2025-02-21/opinion/columns/Koreas-relentless-cycle-of-celebrity-tragedy/2246373\\">asked</a> a question to which no one appears to have an answer: “When will this ever end? How many more lives must be lost before this tragic cycle is broken?”</p><p>Yang’s question, asked in the Korea JoongAng Daily newspaper, is just one of many that has emerged since the actor Kim Sae-ron was found dead in her home in Seoul on Sunday in a case police are treating as suicide. She was 24.</p> <a href=\\"https://www.theguardian.com/world/2025/feb/22/like-a-giant-squid-game-soul-searching-in-south-korea-after-latest-celebrity-suicide\\">Continue reading...</a>"},"tags":[{"term":"South Korea","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/world/south-korea","label":null},{"term":"Asia Pacific","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/world/asia-pacific","label":null},{"term":"Television","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/culture/television","label":null},{"term":"Drama","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/drama","label":null},{"term":"Film","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/film/film","label":null}],"published":"Sat, 22 Feb 2025 00:05:51 GMT","published_parsed":[2025,2,22,0,5,51,5,53,0],"id":"https://www.theguardian.com/world/2025/feb/22/like-a-giant-squid-game-soul-searching-in-south-korea-after-latest-celebrity-suicide","guidislink":false,"media_content":[{"width":"140","url":"https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/bc3890cc605dd376cc8401e38754b7107e1be2e3/0_168_2694_1616/master/2694.jpg?width=140&quality=85&auto=format&fit=max&s=18e779e31513820200401c0b4df3bff8"},{"width":"460","url":"https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/bc3890cc605dd376cc8401e38754b7107e1be2e3/0_168_2694_1616/master/2694.jpg?width=460&quality=85&auto=format&fit=max&s=1c6873ed2c184380fe4e7528af65e720"}],"media_credit":[{"scheme":"urn:ebu","content":"Photograph: AP"},{"scheme":"urn:ebu","content":"Photograph: AP"}],"credit":"Photograph: AP","authors":[{"name":"Raphael Rashid in Seoul and Justin McCurry in Tokyo"}],"author":"Raphael Rashid in Seoul and Justin McCurry in Tokyo","author_detail":{"name":"Raphael Rashid in Seoul and Justin McCurry in Tokyo"},"updated":"2025-02-22T00:05:51Z","updated_parsed":[2025,2,22,0,5,51,5,53,0]},{"title":"‘Traditional flavours and modern ideas’ turn Swedish buns into a TikTok delight","title_detail":{"type":"text/plain","language":null,"base":"","value":"‘Traditional flavours and modern ideas’ turn Swedish buns into a TikTok delight"},"links":[{"rel":"alternate","type":"text/html","href":"https://www.theguardian.com/world/2025/feb/22/traditional-flavours-and-modern-ideas-turn-swedish-buns-into-a-tiktok-delight"}],"link":"https://www.theguardian.com/world/2025/feb/22/traditional-flavours-and-modern-ideas-turn-swedish-buns-into-a-tiktok-delight","summary":"<p>The ‘fantasticallly delicious’ semla has gone from a simple Nordic springtime favourite to a Noma-approved delicacy</p><p>The earliest version of the Swedish <em>semla</em> was a 16th-century plain bread bun served in a soup of warm milk eaten only on Shrove Tuesday in preparation for the 40-day fast of Lent.</p><p>It is a far cry from this year’s hit varieties, which include Dubai chocolate (the chocolate bar with a knafeh and pistachio filling that became a TikTok trend) and <em>chokladboll</em> (based on a Scandinavian oat, cocoa and butter ball – a popular <em>fika</em> item).</p> <a href=\\"https://www.theguardian.com/world/2025/feb/22/traditional-flavours-and-modern-ideas-turn-swedish-buns-into-a-tiktok-delight\\">Continue reading...</a>","summary_detail":{"type":"text/html","language":null,"base":"","value":"<p>The ‘fantasticallly delicious’ semla has gone from a simple Nordic springtime favourite to a Noma-approved delicacy</p><p>The earliest version of the Swedish <em>semla</em> was a 16th-century plain bread bun served in a soup of warm milk eaten only on Shrove Tuesday in preparation for the 40-day fast of Lent.</p><p>It is a far cry from this year’s hit varieties, which include Dubai chocolate (the chocolate bar with a knafeh and pistachio filling that became a TikTok trend) and <em>chokladboll</em> (based on a Scandinavian oat, cocoa and butter ball – a popular <em>fika</em> item).</p> <a href=\\"https://www.theguardian.com/world/2025/feb/22/traditional-flavours-and-modern-ideas-turn-swedish-buns-into-a-tiktok-delight\\">Continue reading...</a>"},"tags":[{"term":"Sweden","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/world/sweden","label":null},{"term":"Social media","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/media/social-media","label":null},{"term":"Cake","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/food/cake","label":null},{"term":"Food","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/food/food","label":null},{"term":"Europe","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/world/europe-news","label":null}],"published":"Sat, 22 Feb 2025 07:00:02 GMT","published_parsed":[2025,2,22,7,0,2,5,53,0],"id":"https://www.theguardian.com/world/2025/feb/22/traditional-flavours-and-modern-ideas-turn-swedish-buns-into-a-tiktok-delight","guidislink":false,"media_content":[{"width":"140","url":"https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/0a677a506dd9e131f1f7cbe5264b29ee7c8e4883/0_201_6071_3645/master/6071.jpg?width=140&quality=85&auto=format&fit=max&s=10a06a776182619af945aa354d5240fb"},{"width":"460","url":"https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/0a677a506dd9e131f1f7cbe5264b29ee7c8e4883/0_201_6071_3645/master/6071.jpg?width=460&quality=85&auto=format&fit=max&s=83809561a7330e984cf85d32a2ef0015"}],"media_credit":[{"scheme":"urn:ebu","content":"Photograph: Rebecka Uhlin/The Guardian"},{"scheme":"urn:ebu","content":"Photograph: Rebecka Uhlin/The Guardian"}],"credit":"Photograph: Rebecka Uhlin/The Guardian","authors":[{"name":"Miranda Bryant Nordic correspondent"}],"author":"Miranda Bryant Nordic correspondent","author_detail":{"name":"Miranda Bryant Nordic correspondent"},"updated":"2025-02-22T07:00:02Z","updated_parsed":[2025,2,22,7,0,2,5,53,0]},{"title":"Bong Joon Ho: ‘I wish I had Ken Loach’s energy, but I’m just thinking about nap time’","title_detail":{"type":"text/plain","language":null,"base":"","value":"Bong Joon Ho: ‘I wish I had Ken Loach’s energy, but I’m just thinking about nap time’"},"links":[{"rel":"alternate","type":"text/html","href":"https://www.theguardian.com/film/2025/feb/22/bong-joon-ho-interview-mickey-17-robert-pattinson-parasite-okja"}],"link":"https://www.theguardian.com/film/2025/feb/22/bong-joon-ho-interview-mickey-17-robert-pattinson-parasite-okja","summary":"<p>How do you follow up an Oscar winner like Parasite? If you’re the South Korean auteur, you make a sci-fi satire where Robert Pattinson dies over and over again. The director discusses the inspirational Loach and Mike Leigh and why it’s hard being a ‘middle-aged film-maker’</p><p>We are in the run-up to the release of Bong Joon Ho’s latest, Mickey 17, and Warner Bros has got the Oscar-winning Korean director stashed away in what appears to be some kind of basement storage room, with grey-painted brickwork and exposed wiring. In fact, this room could pass for one of the “gritty and kind of nasty” cargo-container-packed cabins of his film’s spaceship setting.</p><p>Not that anyone is complaining. Bong, who speaks good English but prefers to conduct interviews via his longtime interpreter Sharon Choi, appears cheerful throughout our conversation, taking occasional sips from a takeaway coffee cup, while dressed in his usual&nbsp;arthouse auteur uniform of a slate-grey blazer over a black T-shirt. He is, for example, completely sanguine about the fact that this follow-up to <a href=\\"https://www.theguardian.com/film/2020/feb/07/parasite-review-bong-joon-ho-south-korean-satire\\">2019’s Parasite</a> is only now reaching our screens, 12 months after its slated release date. Mickey 17<em> </em>wasn’t the only production delayed by 2023’s Screen Actors Guild strikes, he points out, and besides: “My films are quite&nbsp;complicated in terms of distributing and marketing. It’s hard to pinpoint exactly how to package and when to release, because it’s a mix of so many different genres.”</p> <a href=\\"https://www.theguardian.com/film/2025/feb/22/bong-joon-ho-interview-mickey-17-robert-pattinson-parasite-okja\\">Continue reading...</a>","summary_detail":{"type":"text/html","language":null,"base":"","value":"<p>How do you follow up an Oscar winner like Parasite? If you’re the South Korean auteur, you make a sci-fi satire where Robert Pattinson dies over and over again. The director discusses the inspirational Loach and Mike Leigh and why it’s hard being a ‘middle-aged film-maker’</p><p>We are in the run-up to the release of Bong Joon Ho’s latest, Mickey 17, and Warner Bros has got the Oscar-winning Korean director stashed away in what appears to be some kind of basement storage room, with grey-painted brickwork and exposed wiring. In fact, this room could pass for one of the “gritty and kind of nasty” cargo-container-packed cabins of his film’s spaceship setting.</p><p>Not that anyone is complaining. Bong, who speaks good English but prefers to conduct interviews via his longtime interpreter Sharon Choi, appears cheerful throughout our conversation, taking occasional sips from a takeaway coffee cup, while dressed in his usual&nbsp;arthouse auteur uniform of a slate-grey blazer over a black T-shirt. He is, for example, completely sanguine about the fact that this follow-up to <a href=\\"https://www.theguardian.com/film/2020/feb/07/parasite-review-bong-joon-ho-south-korean-satire\\">2019’s Parasite</a> is only now reaching our screens, 12 months after its slated release date. Mickey 17<em> </em>wasn’t the only production delayed by 2023’s Screen Actors Guild strikes, he points out, and besides: “My films are quite&nbsp;complicated in terms of distributing and marketing. It’s hard to pinpoint exactly how to package and when to release, because it’s a mix of so many different genres.”</p> <a href=\\"https://www.theguardian.com/film/2025/feb/22/bong-joon-ho-interview-mickey-17-robert-pattinson-parasite-okja\\">Continue reading...</a>"},"tags":[{"term":"Bong Joon-ho","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/film/bong-joon-ho","label":null},{"term":"Culture","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/culture/culture","label":null},{"term":"Film","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/film/film","label":null}],"published":"Sat, 22 Feb 2025 11:55:05 GMT","published_parsed":[2025,2,22,11,55,5,5,53,0],"id":"https://www.theguardian.com/film/2025/feb/22/bong-joon-ho-interview-mickey-17-robert-pattinson-parasite-okja","guidislink":false,"media_content":[{"width":"140","url":"https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/def074d56feb9fd7dece3a50ef6e9194b0e6245d/0_173_3748_2249/master/3748.jpg?width=140&quality=85&auto=format&fit=max&s=4010c39bf71e7f56159aa29b8e607b42"},{"width":"460","url":"https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/def074d56feb9fd7dece3a50ef6e9194b0e6245d/0_173_3748_2249/master/3748.jpg?width=460&quality=85&auto=format&fit=max&s=a9c17347589ca3654391d736d0752044"}],"media_credit":[{"scheme":"urn:ebu","content":"Photograph: Kurt Iswarienko"},{"scheme":"urn:ebu","content":"Photograph: Kurt Iswarienko"}],"credit":"Photograph: Kurt Iswarienko","authors":[{"name":"Ellen E Jones"}],"author":"Ellen E Jones","author_detail":{"name":"Ellen E Jones"},"updated":"2025-02-22T11:55:05Z","updated_parsed":[2025,2,22,11,55,5,5,53,0]},{"title":"The week in audio: Facing the Music; Tara and George: Last Rights; Why Is Amy in the Bath? and more – review","title_detail":{"type":"text/plain","language":null,"base":"","value":"The week in audio: Facing the Music; Tara and George: Last Rights; Why Is Amy in the Bath? and more – review"},"links":[{"rel":"alternate","type":"text/html","href":"https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2025/feb/22/the-week-in-audio-facing-the-music-radio-3-composers-lives-review-tara-and-george-last-rights-audrey-gillan-why-is-amy-in-the-bath-adams-between-the-ears-a-symphony-of-cicadas"}],"link":"https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2025/feb/22/the-week-in-audio-facing-the-music-radio-3-composers-lives-review-tara-and-george-last-rights-audrey-gillan-why-is-amy-in-the-bath-adams-between-the-ears-a-symphony-of-cicadas","summary":"<p>The lives of Beethoven, Haydn and co enthral; Audrey Gillan updates her award-winning rough sleepers series. Plus, a choir of cicadas and bathtime fun with Amy Adams…</p><p><strong><a href=\\"https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p0kpwq1l\\">Facing the Music</a></strong> Radio 3/BBC Sounds<br /><strong><a href=\\"https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/m0025vbs\\">Tara and George: Last Rights</a></strong> Radio 4/BBC Sounds)<br /><strong><a href=\\"https://podcasts.apple.com/gb/podcast/grab-bag-collab/id1730772365\\">Why Is Amy in the Bath?</a></strong> Grab Bag Collab &amp; Because It’s True Productions<br /><strong><a href=\\"https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/m0027vct\\">Between the Ears: A Symphony of Cicadas</a></strong> Radio 3/BBC Sounds</p><p>“It’s almost midnight,” purrs Dominic West, all honey and velvet, straight after we hear the famously doomy, four-note opening to Beethoven’s Fifth Symphony. The wild-eyed composer is in a cart, West tells us energetically, his latest piano sonata getting ruined by the rain, after throwing some coins at the driver and growling his preferred destination. West relishes every syllable of it: “Vi-ennnn-a!”</p> <a href=\\"https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2025/feb/22/the-week-in-audio-facing-the-music-radio-3-composers-lives-review-tara-and-george-last-rights-audrey-gillan-why-is-amy-in-the-bath-adams-between-the-ears-a-symphony-of-cicadas\\">Continue reading...</a>","summary_detail":{"type":"text/html","language":null,"base":"","value":"<p>The lives of Beethoven, Haydn and co enthral; Audrey Gillan updates her award-winning rough sleepers series. Plus, a choir of cicadas and bathtime fun with Amy Adams…</p><p><strong><a href=\\"https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p0kpwq1l\\">Facing the Music</a></strong> Radio 3/BBC Sounds<br /><strong><a href=\\"https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/m0025vbs\\">Tara and George: Last Rights</a></strong> Radio 4/BBC Sounds)<br /><strong><a href=\\"https://podcasts.apple.com/gb/podcast/grab-bag-collab/id1730772365\\">Why Is Amy in the Bath?</a></strong> Grab Bag Collab &amp; Because It’s True Productions<br /><strong><a href=\\"https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/m0027vct\\">Between the Ears: A Symphony of Cicadas</a></strong> Radio 3/BBC Sounds</p><p>“It’s almost midnight,” purrs Dominic West, all honey and velvet, straight after we hear the famously doomy, four-note opening to Beethoven’s Fifth Symphony. The wild-eyed composer is in a cart, West tells us energetically, his latest piano sonata getting ruined by the rain, after throwing some coins at the driver and growling his preferred destination. West relishes every syllable of it: “Vi-ennnn-a!”</p> <a href=\\"https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2025/feb/22/the-week-in-audio-facing-the-music-radio-3-composers-lives-review-tara-and-george-last-rights-audrey-gillan-why-is-amy-in-the-bath-adams-between-the-ears-a-symphony-of-cicadas\\">Continue reading...</a>"},"tags":[{"term":"Radio","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/culture/radio","label":null},{"term":"Podcasts","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/podcasts","label":null},{"term":"Homelessness","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/society/homelessness","label":null},{"term":"Classical music","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/music/classical-music-and-opera","label":null},{"term":"Amy Adams","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/film/amy-adams","label":null},{"term":"Insects","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/environment/insects","label":null},{"term":"Culture","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/culture/culture","label":null},{"term":"Film","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/film/film","label":null},{"term":"Music","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/music/music","label":null}],"published":"Sat, 22 Feb 2025 17:00:13 GMT","published_parsed":[2025,2,22,17,0,13,5,53,0],"id":"https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2025/feb/22/the-week-in-audio-facing-the-music-radio-3-composers-lives-review-tara-and-george-last-rights-audrey-gillan-why-is-amy-in-the-bath-adams-between-the-ears-a-symphony-of-cicadas","guidislink":false,"media_content":[{"width":"140","url":"https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/8fb5e7e3061f30e31e36dcbd7ee0b101ee5e8f13/0_188_1320_792/master/1320.jpg?width=140&quality=85&auto=format&fit=max&s=92b6ef8459ece78b7b9f92d5bc33e8ad"},{"width":"460","url":"https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/8fb5e7e3061f30e31e36dcbd7ee0b101ee5e8f13/0_188_1320_792/master/1320.jpg?width=460&quality=85&auto=format&fit=max&s=6469a59cbf0a874a55b9a1b09d87252a"}],"media_credit":[{"scheme":"urn:ebu","content":"Photograph: GL Archive/Alamy"},{"scheme":"urn:ebu","content":"Photograph: GL Archive/Alamy"}],"credit":"Photograph: GL Archive/Alamy","authors":[{"name":"Jude Rogers"}],"author":"Jude Rogers","author_detail":{"name":"Jude Rogers"},"updated":"2025-02-22T17:00:13Z","updated_parsed":[2025,2,22,17,0,13,5,53,0]},{"title":"On my radar: Shon Faye’s cultural highlights","title_detail":{"type":"text/plain","language":null,"base":"","value":"On my radar: Shon Faye’s cultural highlights"},"links":[{"rel":"alternate","type":"text/html","href":"https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2025/feb/22/on-my-radar-shon-fayes-cultural-highlights"}],"link":"https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2025/feb/22/on-my-radar-shon-fayes-cultural-highlights","summary":"<p>The author on an obscene drill track, a writing retreat off the coast of Naples and her love of Almodóvar films</p><p>Born in Bristol in 1988, Shon Faye studied English literature at Oxford University and trained as a lawyer before turning to writing. She worked as editor-at-large at <em>Dazed</em>, and has contributed to publications including the <em>Guardian</em>, <em>Vice</em>, Novara and <em>Vogue</em>, where she writes the Dear Shon advice column. She hosts the <em><a href=\\"https://podcasts.apple.com/gb/podcast/call-me-mother-with-shon-faye/id1556479286\\">Call Me Mother</a></em> podcast, for which she interviews LGBTQ+ trailblazers. Faye’s bestselling first book, <em>The Transgender Issue</em>, was published in 2021; her second book, <em>Love in Exile</em>, about the politics of romantic love and relationships, is out now on Allen Lane. She lives in London.</p> <a href=\\"https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2025/feb/22/on-my-radar-shon-fayes-cultural-highlights\\">Continue reading...</a>","summary_detail":{"type":"text/html","language":null,"base":"","value":"<p>The author on an obscene drill track, a writing retreat off the coast of Naples and her love of Almodóvar films</p><p>Born in Bristol in 1988, Shon Faye studied English literature at Oxford University and trained as a lawyer before turning to writing. She worked as editor-at-large at <em>Dazed</em>, and has contributed to publications including the <em>Guardian</em>, <em>Vice</em>, Novara and <em>Vogue</em>, where she writes the Dear Shon advice column. She hosts the <em><a href=\\"https://podcasts.apple.com/gb/podcast/call-me-mother-with-shon-faye/id1556479286\\">Call Me Mother</a></em> podcast, for which she interviews LGBTQ+ trailblazers. Faye’s bestselling first book, <em>The Transgender Issue</em>, was published in 2021; her second book, <em>Love in Exile</em>, about the politics of romantic love and relationships, is out now on Allen Lane. She lives in London.</p> <a href=\\"https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2025/feb/22/on-my-radar-shon-fayes-cultural-highlights\\">Continue reading...</a>"},"tags":[{"term":"Culture","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/culture/culture","label":null},{"term":"Music","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/music/music","label":null},{"term":"Books","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/books/books","label":null},{"term":"Restaurants","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/food/restaurants","label":null},{"term":"Film","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/film/film","label":null},{"term":"Fashion","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/fashion/fashion","label":null},{"term":"Podcasts","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/podcasts","label":null},{"term":"Food","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/food/food","label":null},{"term":"Life and style","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/lifeandstyle","label":null}],"published":"Sat, 22 Feb 2025 15:00:09 GMT","published_parsed":[2025,2,22,15,0,9,5,53,0],"id":"https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2025/feb/22/on-my-radar-shon-fayes-cultural-highlights","guidislink":false,"media_content":[{"width":"140","url":"https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/47ce5c9319f13e84d5a2085cf57285e48e8da6eb/706_295_3947_2368/master/3947.jpg?width=140&quality=85&auto=format&fit=max&s=1577f830dead6643b9671d7d5295efa4"},{"width":"460","url":"https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/47ce5c9319f13e84d5a2085cf57285e48e8da6eb/706_295_3947_2368/master/3947.jpg?width=460&quality=85&auto=format&fit=max&s=972bd2a4f1bf7f9401e84e4ede5cc14d"}],"media_credit":[{"scheme":"urn:ebu","content":"Photograph: Sophia Spring/The Guardian"},{"scheme":"urn:ebu","content":"Photograph: Sophia Spring/The Guardian"}],"credit":"Photograph: Sophia Spring/The Guardian","authors":[{"name":"Kathryn Bromwich"}],"author":"Kathryn Bromwich","author_detail":{"name":"Kathryn Bromwich"},"updated":"2025-02-22T15:00:09Z","updated_parsed":[2025,2,22,15,0,9,5,53,0]},{"title":"‘I do feel we can be too prudish’: one woman’s experience as a life model","title_detail":{"type":"text/plain","language":null,"base":"","value":"‘I do feel we can be too prudish’: one woman’s experience as a life model"},"links":[{"rel":"alternate","type":"text/html","href":"https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2025/feb/22/i-do-feel-we-can-be-too-prudish-one-womans-experience-as-a-life-model"}],"link":"https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2025/feb/22/i-do-feel-we-can-be-too-prudish-one-womans-experience-as-a-life-model","summary":"<p>Life drawing hit the headlines when a north London class, which had been running for more than 30 years, <a href=\\"https://www.standard.co.uk/news/london/row-models-life-drawing-class-hampstead-b1211547.html\\">was told to cover up</a> its naked models or find a new location. Ellie Heney, 32, from Lancaster, has been a life model for 13 years and hopes to be one for the rest of her life. She explains why</p><p>It was my first year of university in Liverpool and it was a typical broke student situation. I saw a poster saying £20 for life modelling and when you’re living on beans on toast you think: ‘Well, I can do that.’ So I gave it a go.</p><p>It’s the strangest thing in the world when you do it for the first time. I remember my heart was pounding and the adrenaline was rushing and the back of my head was prickly because I was thinking: ‘What on earth am I doing? This is crazy!’</p> <a href=\\"https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2025/feb/22/i-do-feel-we-can-be-too-prudish-one-womans-experience-as-a-life-model\\">Continue reading...</a>","summary_detail":{"type":"text/html","language":null,"base":"","value":"<p>Life drawing hit the headlines when a north London class, which had been running for more than 30 years, <a href=\\"https://www.standard.co.uk/news/london/row-models-life-drawing-class-hampstead-b1211547.html\\">was told to cover up</a> its naked models or find a new location. Ellie Heney, 32, from Lancaster, has been a life model for 13 years and hopes to be one for the rest of her life. She explains why</p><p>It was my first year of university in Liverpool and it was a typical broke student situation. I saw a poster saying £20 for life modelling and when you’re living on beans on toast you think: ‘Well, I can do that.’ So I gave it a go.</p><p>It’s the strangest thing in the world when you do it for the first time. I remember my heart was pounding and the adrenaline was rushing and the back of my head was prickly because I was thinking: ‘What on earth am I doing? This is crazy!’</p> <a href=\\"https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2025/feb/22/i-do-feel-we-can-be-too-prudish-one-womans-experience-as-a-life-model\\">Continue reading...</a>"},"tags":[{"term":"Drawing","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/drawing","label":null},{"term":"UK news","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/uk/uk","label":null},{"term":"Art","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/art","label":null}],"published":"Sat, 22 Feb 2025 06:00:03 GMT","published_parsed":[2025,2,22,6,0,3,5,53,0],"id":"https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2025/feb/22/i-do-feel-we-can-be-too-prudish-one-womans-experience-as-a-life-model","guidislink":false,"media_content":[{"width":"140","url":"https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/5ca38d4d413f1bcf3455fff82f174af0cdac957b/0_170_8192_4918/master/8192.jpg?width=140&quality=85&auto=format&fit=max&s=2ec08e4b8e8c2e545f82705e3a04b1d5"},{"width":"460","url":"https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/5ca38d4d413f1bcf3455fff82f174af0cdac957b/0_170_8192_4918/master/8192.jpg?width=460&quality=85&auto=format&fit=max&s=1fca91a2c48754184cf925556f4285ac"}],"media_credit":[{"scheme":"urn:ebu","content":"Photograph: Gary Calton/The Observer"},{"scheme":"urn:ebu","content":"Photograph: Gary Calton/The Observer"}],"credit":"Photograph: Gary Calton/The Observer","authors":[{"name":"Ellie Heney, as told to Mark Brown"}],"author":"Ellie Heney, as told to Mark Brown","author_detail":{"name":"Ellie Heney, as told to Mark Brown"},"updated":"2025-02-22T06:00:03Z","updated_parsed":[2025,2,22,6,0,3,5,53,0]},{"title":"TV tonight: a plucky period drama about sex, drugs and illicit clubs","title_detail":{"type":"text/plain","language":null,"base":"","value":"TV tonight: a plucky period drama about sex, drugs and illicit clubs"},"links":[{"rel":"alternate","type":"text/html","href":"https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2025/feb/22/tv-tonight-a-plucky-period-drama-about-sex-drugs-and-illicit-clubs"}],"link":"https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2025/feb/22/tv-tonight-a-plucky-period-drama-about-sex-drugs-and-illicit-clubs","summary":"<p>Dope Girls is a gritty post-war story set in Soho’s underworld. Plus: Gaelic-language thriller An t-Eilean (The Island). Here’s what to watch this evening</p><p><strong>9.15pm, BBC One</strong></p> <a href=\\"https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2025/feb/22/tv-tonight-a-plucky-period-drama-about-sex-drugs-and-illicit-clubs\\">Continue reading...</a>","summary_detail":{"type":"text/html","language":null,"base":"","value":"<p>Dope Girls is a gritty post-war story set in Soho’s underworld. Plus: Gaelic-language thriller An t-Eilean (The Island). Here’s what to watch this evening</p><p><strong>9.15pm, BBC One</strong></p> <a href=\\"https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2025/feb/22/tv-tonight-a-plucky-period-drama-about-sex-drugs-and-illicit-clubs\\">Continue reading...</a>"},"tags":[{"term":"Television & radio","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/tv-and-radio","label":null},{"term":"Culture","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/culture/culture","label":null}],"published":"Sat, 22 Feb 2025 06:00:05 GMT","published_parsed":[2025,2,22,6,0,5,5,53,0],"id":"https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2025/feb/22/tv-tonight-a-plucky-period-drama-about-sex-drugs-and-illicit-clubs","guidislink":false,"media_content":[{"width":"140","url":"https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/9a9870fa3b8c07b9048dfe8cc596d2f1b9f80683/0_139_4285_2571/master/4285.jpg?width=140&quality=85&auto=format&fit=max&s=acda3c5370f269830549a2c85af907e1"},{"width":"460","url":"https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/9a9870fa3b8c07b9048dfe8cc596d2f1b9f80683/0_139_4285_2571/master/4285.jpg?width=460&quality=85&auto=format&fit=max&s=a6ca4d0437ab52225c6ff843502154a3"}],"media_credit":[{"scheme":"urn:ebu","content":"Photograph: Kevin Baker/BBC/Bad Wolf"},{"scheme":"urn:ebu","content":"Photograph: Kevin Baker/BBC/Bad Wolf"}],"credit":"Photograph: Kevin Baker/BBC/Bad Wolf","authors":[{"name":"Hollie Richardson, Graeme Virtue, Ali Catterall,  Phil Harrison and Simon Wardell"}],"author":"Hollie Richardson, Graeme Virtue, Ali Catterall,  Phil Harrison and Simon Wardell","author_detail":{"name":"Hollie Richardson, Graeme Virtue, Ali Catterall,  Phil Harrison and Simon Wardell"},"updated":"2025-02-22T06:00:05Z","updated_parsed":[2025,2,22,6,0,5,5,53,0]},{"title":"‘The essential ingredient is openness’: Curtis Sittenfeld on the deep joy of midlife friendship","title_detail":{"type":"text/plain","language":null,"base":"","value":"‘The essential ingredient is openness’: Curtis Sittenfeld on the deep joy of midlife friendship"},"links":[{"rel":"alternate","type":"text/html","href":"https://www.theguardian.com/books/2025/feb/22/the-essential-ingredient-is-openess-curtis-sittenfeld-on-the-deep-joy-of-midlife-friendship"}],"link":"https://www.theguardian.com/books/2025/feb/22/the-essential-ingredient-is-openess-curtis-sittenfeld-on-the-deep-joy-of-midlife-friendship","summary":"<p>Friendships become closer as you get older argues the novelist, because by middle age everyone has faced dramatic challenges, disappointments and sorrows – and being honest about them is a powerful point of bonding</p><p>My ninth book is published this week, and in recent years I’ve described my writing like this: I take care with my sentences, but exquisite prose isn’t my goal. My goal is to give the reader the feeling that you – and by you, I mean me – have when you’re going for a long walk with a close friend, and the friend says: “The craziest thing just happened to me.” <em>What?!</em> You think and possibly say. <em>Tell me immediately! </em>And then what happened, and then what happened? As a writer, this is the urgency I’m chasing, this is the investment, the richness of emotion, the confiding and closeness and <em>caring</em>.</p><p>A line in Miranda July’s 2024 novel <a href=\\"https://www.theguardian.com/books/article/2024/may/16/all-fours-by-miranda-july-review-larger-than-life\\">All Fours</a>, a book I’ve discussed with many friends, perfectly captures for me this sense of participating in a bottomless conversation: “I was often two or three hours late because I had trouble admitting that I was planning to talk to Jordi for five hours.”</p> <a href=\\"https://www.theguardian.com/books/2025/feb/22/the-essential-ingredient-is-openess-curtis-sittenfeld-on-the-deep-joy-of-midlife-friendship\\">Continue reading...</a>","summary_detail":{"type":"text/html","language":null,"base":"","value":"<p>Friendships become closer as you get older argues the novelist, because by middle age everyone has faced dramatic challenges, disappointments and sorrows – and being honest about them is a powerful point of bonding</p><p>My ninth book is published this week, and in recent years I’ve described my writing like this: I take care with my sentences, but exquisite prose isn’t my goal. My goal is to give the reader the feeling that you – and by you, I mean me – have when you’re going for a long walk with a close friend, and the friend says: “The craziest thing just happened to me.” <em>What?!</em> You think and possibly say. <em>Tell me immediately! </em>And then what happened, and then what happened? As a writer, this is the urgency I’m chasing, this is the investment, the richness of emotion, the confiding and closeness and <em>caring</em>.</p><p>A line in Miranda July’s 2024 novel <a href=\\"https://www.theguardian.com/books/article/2024/may/16/all-fours-by-miranda-july-review-larger-than-life\\">All Fours</a>, a book I’ve discussed with many friends, perfectly captures for me this sense of participating in a bottomless conversation: “I was often two or three hours late because I had trouble admitting that I was planning to talk to Jordi for five hours.”</p> <a href=\\"https://www.theguardian.com/books/2025/feb/22/the-essential-ingredient-is-openess-curtis-sittenfeld-on-the-deep-joy-of-midlife-friendship\\">Continue reading...</a>"},"tags":[{"term":"Books","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/books/books","label":null},{"term":"Curtis Sittenfeld","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/books/curtis-sittenfeld","label":null},{"term":"Culture","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/culture/culture","label":null},{"term":"Friendship","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/friendship","label":null},{"term":"Fiction","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/books/fiction","label":null}],"published":"Sat, 22 Feb 2025 11:00:05 GMT","published_parsed":[2025,2,22,11,0,5,5,53,0],"id":"https://www.theguardian.com/books/2025/feb/22/the-essential-ingredient-is-openess-curtis-sittenfeld-on-the-deep-joy-of-midlife-friendship","guidislink":false,"media_content":[{"width":"140","url":"https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/62a373e9780c59a92cf8b54c79a35aba174aa69e/26_1346_3181_1908/master/3181.jpg?width=140&quality=85&auto=format&fit=max&s=87d9b57f3beeaa5a1fe257963de4ea16"},{"width":"460","url":"https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/62a373e9780c59a92cf8b54c79a35aba174aa69e/26_1346_3181_1908/master/3181.jpg?width=460&quality=85&auto=format&fit=max&s=fe72f3d14a2964c3e254474d896ba822"}],"media_credit":[{"scheme":"urn:ebu","content":"Photograph: Jenn Ackerman"},{"scheme":"urn:ebu","content":"Photograph: Jenn Ackerman"}],"credit":"Photograph: Jenn Ackerman","authors":[{"name":"Curtis Sittenfeld"}],"author":"Curtis Sittenfeld","author_detail":{"name":"Curtis Sittenfeld"},"updated":"2025-02-22T11:00:05Z","updated_parsed":[2025,2,22,11,0,5,5,53,0]},{"title":"‘More like vegetable cooking water’: the best (and worst) supermarket chicken soup","title_detail":{"type":"text/plain","language":null,"base":"","value":"‘More like vegetable cooking water’: the best (and worst) supermarket chicken soup"},"links":[{"rel":"alternate","type":"text/html","href":"https://www.theguardian.com/thefilter/2025/feb/22/best-chicken-vegetable-soup"}],"link":"https://www.theguardian.com/thefilter/2025/feb/22/best-chicken-vegetable-soup","summary":"<p>Whose soup is a chunky triumph? And whose is a sludgy mess? Felicity Cloake tries out supermarket takes on chilled, ready-made chicken and vegetable soup</p><p>• <strong><a href=\\"https://www.theguardian.com/thefilter/2025/jan/07/best-blenders\\">The best blenders to blitz like a pro, tried and tested</a></strong></p><p>As a small child, my dream was to open an underwater restaurant (no, me neither), and the short menu I painstakingly wrote out for said venture started with chicken and vegetable soup. Which is to say, I have history with this dish. It feels familiar, comforting and overwhelmingly wholesome, yet I don’t often eat it these days, not least because I’ve never found one commercially that makes any welfare claims for the chicken concerned (and I’m generally too cheap to make it myself).</p><p>So I was quite excited about this particular taste test – and perhaps inevitably disappointed that even the most expensive samples gave so little information about the provenance of their meat. That said, with a handful of exceptions, the standard was pretty high flavour-wise, and Aldi, Marks &amp; Spencer, Morrisons and Sainsbury’s all at least note that they use British chicken, which is a start.</p> <a href=\\"https://www.theguardian.com/thefilter/2025/feb/22/best-chicken-vegetable-soup\\">Continue reading...</a>","summary_detail":{"type":"text/html","language":null,"base":"","value":"<p>Whose soup is a chunky triumph? And whose is a sludgy mess? Felicity Cloake tries out supermarket takes on chilled, ready-made chicken and vegetable soup</p><p>• <strong><a href=\\"https://www.theguardian.com/thefilter/2025/jan/07/best-blenders\\">The best blenders to blitz like a pro, tried and tested</a></strong></p><p>As a small child, my dream was to open an underwater restaurant (no, me neither), and the short menu I painstakingly wrote out for said venture started with chicken and vegetable soup. Which is to say, I have history with this dish. It feels familiar, comforting and overwhelmingly wholesome, yet I don’t often eat it these days, not least because I’ve never found one commercially that makes any welfare claims for the chicken concerned (and I’m generally too cheap to make it myself).</p><p>So I was quite excited about this particular taste test – and perhaps inevitably disappointed that even the most expensive samples gave so little information about the provenance of their meat. That said, with a handful of exceptions, the standard was pretty high flavour-wise, and Aldi, Marks &amp; Spencer, Morrisons and Sainsbury’s all at least note that they use British chicken, which is a start.</p> <a href=\\"https://www.theguardian.com/thefilter/2025/feb/22/best-chicken-vegetable-soup\\">Continue reading...</a>"},"tags":[{"term":"Food","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/food/food","label":null},{"term":"Life and style","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/lifeandstyle","label":null},{"term":"Soup","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/food/soup","label":null},{"term":"Chicken","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/food/chicken","label":null},{"term":"Vegetables","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/food/vegetables","label":null},{"term":"Meat","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/food/meat","label":null}],"published":"Sat, 22 Feb 2025 10:00:03 GMT","published_parsed":[2025,2,22,10,0,3,5,53,0],"id":"https://www.theguardian.com/thefilter/2025/feb/22/best-chicken-vegetable-soup","guidislink":false,"media_content":[{"width":"140","url":"https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/3b03939faf0f01311870dd773ad9796a60f76fdc/403_1723_6923_4154/master/6923.jpg?width=140&quality=85&auto=format&fit=max&s=e7d43469b65b3c82c06e68b2bb4da6ea"},{"width":"460","url":"https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/3b03939faf0f01311870dd773ad9796a60f76fdc/403_1723_6923_4154/master/6923.jpg?width=460&quality=85&auto=format&fit=max&s=89840fcb13387a063f32095daa1d43af"}],"media_credit":[{"scheme":"urn:ebu","content":"Photograph: Robert Billington/The Guardian"},{"scheme":"urn:ebu","content":"Photograph: Robert Billington/The Guardian"}],"credit":"Photograph: Robert Billington/The Guardian","authors":[{"name":"Felicity Cloake"}],"author":"Felicity Cloake","author_detail":{"name":"Felicity Cloake"},"updated":"2025-02-22T10:00:03Z","updated_parsed":[2025,2,22,10,0,3,5,53,0]},{"title":"I’m obsessed with finding the perfect pillow. These six favourites prove there’s one for every sleeper","title_detail":{"type":"text/plain","language":null,"base":"","value":"I’m obsessed with finding the perfect pillow. These six favourites prove there’s one for every sleeper"},"links":[{"rel":"alternate","type":"text/html","href":"https://www.theguardian.com/thefilter/2025/feb/21/best-anti-allergy-hypoallergenic-pillows"}],"link":"https://www.theguardian.com/thefilter/2025/feb/21/best-anti-allergy-hypoallergenic-pillows","summary":"<p>From feather-free to vegan down, we tested (and tussled with) 17 pillows to reveal the best</p><p><strong>• <a href=\\"https://www.theguardian.com/thefilter/2025/feb/06/best-mattress\\">The best mattresses: sleep better with our six rigorously tested picks</a></strong></p><p>We spend about a third of our lives sleeping – or trying to do so – and feeling comfortable and well supported during slumber is crucial. But all too often, our pillows let us down. I can’t be the only person to have bought a comfy-feeling pillow from a reputable brand only to feel it becoming increasingly flat or lumpy with time, or after putting it through the wash.</p><p>Synthetic pillows are touted as a squishy yet supportive alternative to traditional feather and down pillows, and they’re versatile and easy to clean. Plus, they’re a great option for people with asthma, or dust and feather allergies, like me.</p><p><strong>Best synthetic pillow overall:</strong><br />\\n Brightr Nox vegan down pillow<br /><a href=\\"https://www.brightrsleep.com/products/brightr%C2%AE-sleep-nox-adjustable-pillow\\"><sub>£79.99 at Brightr Sleep</sub></a></p><p><strong>Best pillow for side sleepers:</strong> <br />\\n Hanse Select feather-free pillow<br /><a href=\\"https://www.hansetextil.co.uk/hans-pillow-featherfree.html\\"><sub>From €99 (about £82) at Hanse </sub></a></p><p><strong>Best pillow for back sleepers:</strong> <br />\\n Richard Haworth Soft micro-down hypoallergenic pillow<br /><a href=\\"https://www.richardhaworth.co.uk/bed-protection/pillows/micro-down-pillows\\"><sub>£26.36 at Richard Haworth</sub></a></p> <a href=\\"https://www.theguardian.com/thefilter/2025/feb/21/best-anti-allergy-hypoallergenic-pillows\\">Continue reading...</a>","summary_detail":{"type":"text/html","language":null,"base":"","value":"<p>From feather-free to vegan down, we tested (and tussled with) 17 pillows to reveal the best</p><p><strong>• <a href=\\"https://www.theguardian.com/thefilter/2025/feb/06/best-mattress\\">The best mattresses: sleep better with our six rigorously tested picks</a></strong></p><p>We spend about a third of our lives sleeping – or trying to do so – and feeling comfortable and well supported during slumber is crucial. But all too often, our pillows let us down. I can’t be the only person to have bought a comfy-feeling pillow from a reputable brand only to feel it becoming increasingly flat or lumpy with time, or after putting it through the wash.</p><p>Synthetic pillows are touted as a squishy yet supportive alternative to traditional feather and down pillows, and they’re versatile and easy to clean. Plus, they’re a great option for people with asthma, or dust and feather allergies, like me.</p><p><strong>Best synthetic pillow overall:</strong><br />\\n Brightr Nox vegan down pillow<br /><a href=\\"https://www.brightrsleep.com/products/brightr%C2%AE-sleep-nox-adjustable-pillow\\"><sub>£79.99 at Brightr Sleep</sub></a></p><p><strong>Best pillow for side sleepers:</strong> <br />\\n Hanse Select feather-free pillow<br /><a href=\\"https://www.hansetextil.co.uk/hans-pillow-featherfree.html\\"><sub>From €99 (about £82) at Hanse </sub></a></p><p><strong>Best pillow for back sleepers:</strong> <br />\\n Richard Haworth Soft micro-down hypoallergenic pillow<br /><a href=\\"https://www.richardhaworth.co.uk/bed-protection/pillows/micro-down-pillows\\"><sub>£26.36 at Richard Haworth</sub></a></p> <a href=\\"https://www.theguardian.com/thefilter/2025/feb/21/best-anti-allergy-hypoallergenic-pillows\\">Continue reading...</a>"},"tags":[{"term":"Sleep","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/sleep","label":null},{"term":"Homes","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/homes","label":null},{"term":"Life and style","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/lifeandstyle","label":null},{"term":"Health & wellbeing","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/health-and-wellbeing","label":null},{"term":"Interiors","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/interiors","label":null}],"published":"Fri, 21 Feb 2025 15:00:40 GMT","published_parsed":[2025,2,21,15,0,40,4,52,0],"id":"https://www.theguardian.com/thefilter/2025/feb/21/best-anti-allergy-hypoallergenic-pillows","guidislink":false,"media_content":[{"width":"140","url":"https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/ab7764489828f515bf75d888584612caed313e24/0_205_4032_2419/master/4032.jpg?width=140&quality=85&auto=format&fit=max&s=3e1fac018784a351418aa4a94594d778"},{"width":"460","url":"https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/ab7764489828f515bf75d888584612caed313e24/0_205_4032_2419/master/4032.jpg?width=460&quality=85&auto=format&fit=max&s=1cfdac203800afd0ea6a3430ffe0b53f"}],"media_credit":[{"scheme":"urn:ebu","content":"Photograph: Linda Geddes/The Guardian"},{"scheme":"urn:ebu","content":"Photograph: Linda Geddes/The Guardian"}],"credit":"Photograph: Linda Geddes/The Guardian","authors":[{"name":"Linda Geddes"}],"author":"Linda Geddes","author_detail":{"name":"Linda Geddes"},"updated":"2025-02-21T15:00:40Z","updated_parsed":[2025,2,21,15,0,40,4,52,0]},{"title":"‘The classiest gift I’ve heard of’: what to bring to a dinner party (that isn’t wine or chocolates)","title_detail":{"type":"text/plain","language":null,"base":"","value":"‘The classiest gift I’ve heard of’: what to bring to a dinner party (that isn’t wine or chocolates)"},"links":[{"rel":"alternate","type":"text/html","href":"https://www.theguardian.com/thefilter/2025/feb/19/what-to-bring-dinner-party"}],"link":"https://www.theguardian.com/thefilter/2025/feb/19/what-to-bring-dinner-party","summary":"<p>From fancy olive oil to jazzy tea towels, skip the obvious and surprise your host with one of these creative dinner party gifts</p><p>I’m convinced that the same bottle of Whispering Angel and box of Lindor chocolates have been doing the rounds among my friends for two or three years now. It’s not that we don’t like them (what’s not to like?); it’s that they are such easy gifts. Every host saves them for when they’re next a guest, in an unspoken game of Pass the Provençal Rose.</p><p>Yet the reason wine and chocolates are such popular dinner party gifts is the same reason they get passed around: they’re often generic. They’re not thoughtless per se, but they rarely suggest a huge amount of thought for the personality or taste of the host.</p> <a href=\\"https://www.theguardian.com/thefilter/2025/feb/19/what-to-bring-dinner-party\\">Continue reading...</a>","summary_detail":{"type":"text/html","language":null,"base":"","value":"<p>From fancy olive oil to jazzy tea towels, skip the obvious and surprise your host with one of these creative dinner party gifts</p><p>I’m convinced that the same bottle of Whispering Angel and box of Lindor chocolates have been doing the rounds among my friends for two or three years now. It’s not that we don’t like them (what’s not to like?); it’s that they are such easy gifts. Every host saves them for when they’re next a guest, in an unspoken game of Pass the Provençal Rose.</p><p>Yet the reason wine and chocolates are such popular dinner party gifts is the same reason they get passed around: they’re often generic. They’re not thoughtless per se, but they rarely suggest a huge amount of thought for the personality or taste of the host.</p> <a href=\\"https://www.theguardian.com/thefilter/2025/feb/19/what-to-bring-dinner-party\\">Continue reading...</a>"},"tags":[{"term":"Life and style","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/lifeandstyle","label":null}],"published":"Wed, 19 Feb 2025 15:00:11 GMT","published_parsed":[2025,2,19,15,0,11,2,50,0],"id":"https://www.theguardian.com/thefilter/2025/feb/19/what-to-bring-dinner-party","guidislink":false,"media_content":[{"width":"140","url":"https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/545e9effb5e717ea28f7d639571f081d9e3d9dc4/0_45_7952_4774/master/7952.jpg?width=140&quality=85&auto=format&fit=max&s=8728dea362419a966ccedeb8307bbf1c"},{"width":"460","url":"https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/545e9effb5e717ea28f7d639571f081d9e3d9dc4/0_45_7952_4774/master/7952.jpg?width=460&quality=85&auto=format&fit=max&s=436023ce6b6143500f02d35a9226171e"}],"media_credit":[{"scheme":"urn:ebu","content":"Photograph: miniseries/Getty Images"},{"scheme":"urn:ebu","content":"Photograph: miniseries/Getty Images"}],"credit":"Photograph: miniseries/Getty Images","authors":[{"name":"Clare Finney"}],"author":"Clare Finney","author_detail":{"name":"Clare Finney"},"updated":"2025-02-19T15:00:11Z","updated_parsed":[2025,2,19,15,0,11,2,50,0]},{"title":"15 of the best men’s jumpers, from cashmere and cable knit to merino wool","title_detail":{"type":"text/plain","language":null,"base":"","value":"15 of the best men’s jumpers, from cashmere and cable knit to merino wool"},"links":[{"rel":"alternate","type":"text/html","href":"https://www.theguardian.com/thefilter/2025/feb/18/best-mens-jumpers"}],"link":"https://www.theguardian.com/thefilter/2025/feb/18/best-mens-jumpers","summary":"<p>Whether you’re searching for a lamb’s wool layer or a stylish sweater vest, upgrade your knitwear with these instant classics</p><p>• <strong><a href=\\"https://www.theguardian.com/thefilter/2025/jan/08/best-mens-boots\\">The best boots for men: 14 favourites, from Chelsea to brogues to western</a></strong></p><p>Knitwear, like most menswear, is best done classic. As with other staples – denim, T-shirts, tailoring et al – it’s an investment that will go beyond any trend or season. So, if you buy the right pieces, you’ll likely wear them for years to come.</p><p>With that in mind, there are a few things to consider when hitting the shops. Above all, it’s best to choose jumpers you <em>know</em> are made well, using good fabrics. That means you should go for brands you can trust in terms of craftsmanship and stick to natural fibres, such as cotton, wool and cashmere. Unlike human-made textiles, these are naturally breathable and temperature-regulating so they’re more comfortable and better for your skin. This sometimes means the price is a little higher than a fast-fashion buy, but they tend to last longer – just be sure to keep them protected when moth season hits.</p> <a href=\\"https://www.theguardian.com/thefilter/2025/feb/18/best-mens-jumpers\\">Continue reading...</a>","summary_detail":{"type":"text/html","language":null,"base":"","value":"<p>Whether you’re searching for a lamb’s wool layer or a stylish sweater vest, upgrade your knitwear with these instant classics</p><p>• <strong><a href=\\"https://www.theguardian.com/thefilter/2025/jan/08/best-mens-boots\\">The best boots for men: 14 favourites, from Chelsea to brogues to western</a></strong></p><p>Knitwear, like most menswear, is best done classic. As with other staples – denim, T-shirts, tailoring et al – it’s an investment that will go beyond any trend or season. So, if you buy the right pieces, you’ll likely wear them for years to come.</p><p>With that in mind, there are a few things to consider when hitting the shops. Above all, it’s best to choose jumpers you <em>know</em> are made well, using good fabrics. That means you should go for brands you can trust in terms of craftsmanship and stick to natural fibres, such as cotton, wool and cashmere. Unlike human-made textiles, these are naturally breathable and temperature-regulating so they’re more comfortable and better for your skin. This sometimes means the price is a little higher than a fast-fashion buy, but they tend to last longer – just be sure to keep them protected when moth season hits.</p> <a href=\\"https://www.theguardian.com/thefilter/2025/feb/18/best-mens-jumpers\\">Continue reading...</a>"},"tags":[{"term":"Men\'s fashion","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/fashion/mens-fashion","label":null},{"term":"Men\'s tops","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/fashion/mens-tops","label":null},{"term":"Life and style","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/lifeandstyle","label":null},{"term":"Fashion","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/fashion/fashion","label":null},{"term":"Men","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/men","label":null}],"published":"Tue, 18 Feb 2025 16:00:09 GMT","published_parsed":[2025,2,18,16,0,9,1,49,0],"id":"https://www.theguardian.com/thefilter/2025/feb/18/best-mens-jumpers","guidislink":false,"media_content":[{"width":"140","url":"https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/fb5c94f5bcf7614bfbdbf3e57f79744838590a10/0_548_2005_1203/master/2005.jpg?width=140&quality=85&auto=format&fit=max&s=f99a3245a5c4332a32be7f5e2df10f7b"},{"width":"460","url":"https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/fb5c94f5bcf7614bfbdbf3e57f79744838590a10/0_548_2005_1203/master/2005.jpg?width=460&quality=85&auto=format&fit=max&s=c75acd4710748c31d35890979f2416ea"}],"media_credit":[{"scheme":"urn:ebu","content":"Photograph: PR Image"},{"scheme":"urn:ebu","content":"Photograph: PR Image"}],"credit":"Photograph: PR Image","authors":[{"name":"Peter Bevan"}],"author":"Peter Bevan","author_detail":{"name":"Peter Bevan"},"updated":"2025-02-18T16:00:09Z","updated_parsed":[2025,2,18,16,0,9,1,49,0]},{"title":"Agnès B: ‘I hate fashion. It’s not interesting.’","title_detail":{"type":"text/plain","language":null,"base":"","value":"Agnès B: ‘I hate fashion. It’s not interesting.’"},"links":[{"rel":"alternate","type":"text/html","href":"https://www.theguardian.com/fashion/2025/feb/22/agnes-b-i-hate-fashion-its-not-interesting"}],"link":"https://www.theguardian.com/fashion/2025/feb/22/agnes-b-i-hate-fashion-its-not-interesting","summary":"<p>The designer, 83, talks about her troubled childhood, love of art, and how she persuaded David Bowie to drop the dodgy brown suits</p><p><strong>During World War Two</strong> I remember standing in total darkness in a corridor at our home in Versailles, listening to the bombs. I was two years old. The sound scared me so much that my parents sent me to their dear friends’ farm in Normandy, where I stayed for a long time. They called me “Lamb” and I called them “Shepherd’ and ‘Shepherdess”.<br /><br /><strong>Mother was complicated:</strong> strict, sometimes very nervous, often furious for no reason. She fought a lot with my father. Inside and outside the house, she was two different people. The life she wanted was with her lover, but back then you didn’t get divorced.<br /><br /><strong>Everyone in the family</strong> knew I was my father’s preferred daughter. My sisters accepted it because they could see how alike we were. Bruno Troublé, my funny, interesting brother, was known as “<em>le ravissant</em>” – “the ravishing” – by my mother. He was her favourite.</p><p><strong>When I left my first marriage</strong> to Christian Bourgois, aged 20, I had no money. He paid my rent; the rest I had to manage. I sold my wedding jewellery and some furniture so I could feed our two children. Christian was an important literary publisher, but not a great husband. I kept the “B” for my surname, though.<br /><br /><strong>Nice girls are always in danger.</strong> I broke my leg when I was 12 and had to stay at home for a month. My uncle came to see me every night and abused me. He was a great man, with three children, but he loved me too much. It inspired my film, <em><a href=\\"https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/oct/16/my-name-is-hmmm-je-mappelle-review-agnes-b\\">My Name Is Hmmm</a></em>, about a girl who was abused by her father.<br /><br /><strong>The first Agnès B</strong> <strong>store</strong> in Paris was full of birds. We had two in a cage, then opened the door once they had babies. They added stray threads from the clothes to their nests and were very happy. In the end we had 35 birds, flying around to the sounds of Bob Marley and Roxy Music on the stereo.<br /><br /><strong>David Bowie wore</strong> an awful brown pleated suit when I saw him in concert. I sent him a pair of black leather jeans with a note in the pocket that said “You should stick to a rock ’n’ roll style.” He bought more pieces from me, then I dressed him for 25 years including his 50th birthday at Madison Square Garden.</p> <a href=\\"https://www.theguardian.com/fashion/2025/feb/22/agnes-b-i-hate-fashion-its-not-interesting\\">Continue reading...</a>","summary_detail":{"type":"text/html","language":null,"base":"","value":"<p>The designer, 83, talks about her troubled childhood, love of art, and how she persuaded David Bowie to drop the dodgy brown suits</p><p><strong>During World War Two</strong> I remember standing in total darkness in a corridor at our home in Versailles, listening to the bombs. I was two years old. The sound scared me so much that my parents sent me to their dear friends’ farm in Normandy, where I stayed for a long time. They called me “Lamb” and I called them “Shepherd’ and ‘Shepherdess”.<br /><br /><strong>Mother was complicated:</strong> strict, sometimes very nervous, often furious for no reason. She fought a lot with my father. Inside and outside the house, she was two different people. The life she wanted was with her lover, but back then you didn’t get divorced.<br /><br /><strong>Everyone in the family</strong> knew I was my father’s preferred daughter. My sisters accepted it because they could see how alike we were. Bruno Troublé, my funny, interesting brother, was known as “<em>le ravissant</em>” – “the ravishing” – by my mother. He was her favourite.</p><p><strong>When I left my first marriage</strong> to Christian Bourgois, aged 20, I had no money. He paid my rent; the rest I had to manage. I sold my wedding jewellery and some furniture so I could feed our two children. Christian was an important literary publisher, but not a great husband. I kept the “B” for my surname, though.<br /><br /><strong>Nice girls are always in danger.</strong> I broke my leg when I was 12 and had to stay at home for a month. My uncle came to see me every night and abused me. He was a great man, with three children, but he loved me too much. It inspired my film, <em><a href=\\"https://www.theguardian.com/film/2014/oct/16/my-name-is-hmmm-je-mappelle-review-agnes-b\\">My Name Is Hmmm</a></em>, about a girl who was abused by her father.<br /><br /><strong>The first Agnès B</strong> <strong>store</strong> in Paris was full of birds. We had two in a cage, then opened the door once they had babies. They added stray threads from the clothes to their nests and were very happy. In the end we had 35 birds, flying around to the sounds of Bob Marley and Roxy Music on the stereo.<br /><br /><strong>David Bowie wore</strong> an awful brown pleated suit when I saw him in concert. I sent him a pair of black leather jeans with a note in the pocket that said “You should stick to a rock ’n’ roll style.” He bought more pieces from me, then I dressed him for 25 years including his 50th birthday at Madison Square Garden.</p> <a href=\\"https://www.theguardian.com/fashion/2025/feb/22/agnes-b-i-hate-fashion-its-not-interesting\\">Continue reading...</a>"},"tags":[{"term":"Fashion","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/fashion/fashion","label":null},{"term":"Life and style","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/lifeandstyle","label":null},{"term":"David Bowie","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/music/davidbowie","label":null},{"term":"Music","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/music/music","label":null},{"term":"Culture","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/culture/culture","label":null}],"published":"Sat, 22 Feb 2025 14:00:09 GMT","published_parsed":[2025,2,22,14,0,9,5,53,0],"id":"https://www.theguardian.com/fashion/2025/feb/22/agnes-b-i-hate-fashion-its-not-interesting","guidislink":false,"media_content":[{"width":"140","url":"https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/d7d3f7842b96671b0438abb455d600928b053dca/318_1180_2861_1716/master/2861.jpg?width=140&quality=85&auto=format&fit=max&s=0dccae87ababbd12c94f89ca9dd09450"},{"width":"460","url":"https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/d7d3f7842b96671b0438abb455d600928b053dca/318_1180_2861_1716/master/2861.jpg?width=460&quality=85&auto=format&fit=max&s=d9aaefddc97cc28e7fb4c04e77099f62"}],"media_credit":[{"scheme":"urn:ebu","content":"Photograph: Antoine Doyen/The Observer"},{"scheme":"urn:ebu","content":"Photograph: Antoine Doyen/The Observer"}],"credit":"Photograph: Antoine Doyen/The Observer","authors":[{"name":"Hayley Myers"}],"author":"Hayley Myers","author_detail":{"name":"Hayley Myers"},"updated":"2025-02-22T14:00:09Z","updated_parsed":[2025,2,22,14,0,9,5,53,0]},{"title":"This is how we do it: ‘At 78, I’m having multiple orgasms, thanks to erection injections – and marijuana’","title_detail":{"type":"text/plain","language":null,"base":"","value":"This is how we do it: ‘At 78, I’m having multiple orgasms, thanks to erection injections – and marijuana’"},"links":[{"rel":"alternate","type":"text/html","href":"https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2025/feb/22/this-is-how-we-do-it-at-78-im-having-multiple-orgasms-thanks-to-erection-injections-and-marijuana"}],"link":"https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2025/feb/22/this-is-how-we-do-it-at-78-im-having-multiple-orgasms-thanks-to-erection-injections-and-marijuana","summary":"<p>When Dean started having erectile problems, his wife Gaby insisted he get some help. Now they both have pleasure galore in bed</p><p><strong><a href=\\"https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2022/sep/08/would-you-and-your-sexual-partner-like-to-share-the-story-of-what-you-get-up-to-in-the-bedroom\\">How do you do it? Share the story of your sex life, anonymously</a></strong></p><p>We can have sex for an hour or two and I can have multiple orgasms without ejaculating. Then I read erotic literature and ejaculate, and that’s that</p> <a href=\\"https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2025/feb/22/this-is-how-we-do-it-at-78-im-having-multiple-orgasms-thanks-to-erection-injections-and-marijuana\\">Continue reading...</a>","summary_detail":{"type":"text/html","language":null,"base":"","value":"<p>When Dean started having erectile problems, his wife Gaby insisted he get some help. Now they both have pleasure galore in bed</p><p><strong><a href=\\"https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2022/sep/08/would-you-and-your-sexual-partner-like-to-share-the-story-of-what-you-get-up-to-in-the-bedroom\\">How do you do it? Share the story of your sex life, anonymously</a></strong></p><p>We can have sex for an hour or two and I can have multiple orgasms without ejaculating. Then I read erotic literature and ejaculate, and that’s that</p> <a href=\\"https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2025/feb/22/this-is-how-we-do-it-at-78-im-having-multiple-orgasms-thanks-to-erection-injections-and-marijuana\\">Continue reading...</a>"},"tags":[{"term":"Sex","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/sex","label":null},{"term":"Relationships","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/relationships","label":null},{"term":"Life and style","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/lifeandstyle","label":null},{"term":"Older people","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/society/older-people","label":null},{"term":"Society","scheme":"https://www.theguardian.com/society/society","label":null}],"published":"Sat, 22 Feb 2025 12:00:07 GMT","published_parsed":[2025,2,22,12,0,7,5,53,0],"id":"https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2025/feb/22/this-is-how-we-do-it-at-78-im-having-multiple-orgasms-thanks-to-erection-injections-and-marijuana","guidislink":false,"media_content":[{"width":"140","url":"https://i.guim.co.uk/img/media/c4cc930017e7faf79c06967197ccbf3340ba0072/8_0_1483_890/master/1483.jpg?width=140&qua